Package: xlog2-gtk
Architecture: any
Depends: ${shlibs:Depends}, ${misc:Depends}
Recommends: tqsl, xlog2-data
Description: amateur-radio logging program (GTK 4 frontend)
 xlog2 is an amateur-radio logger: it logs QSOs to SQLite, exchanges ADIF,
 receives logged QSOs over UDP (WSJT-X / fldigi / JTAlert), controls a radio
 via Hamlib, looks up calls on QRZ.com, drives a network CW keyer, shows a
 DX-cluster band map, and syncs with ARRL's Logbook of The World.
 .
 This package provides the GTK 4 (gtkmm) frontend, xlog2-gtk.

Package: xlog2-qt
Architecture: any
Depends: ${shlibs:Depends}, ${misc:Depends}
Recommends: tqsl, xlog2-data
Description: amateur-radio logging program (Qt frontend)
 xlog2 is an amateur-radio logger: it logs QSOs to SQLite, exchanges ADIF,
 receives logged QSOs over UDP (WSJT-X / fldigi / JTAlert), controls a radio
 via Hamlib, looks up calls on QRZ.com, drives a network CW keyer, shows a
 DX-cluster band map, and syncs with ARRL's Logbook of The World.
 .
 This package provides the Qt Widgets frontend, xlog2-qt. It reads and writes
 the same logbooks and settings as xlog2-gtk.

Package: xlog2-syncd
Architecture: any
Depends: ${shlibs:Depends}, ${misc:Depends}
Description: amateur-radio logging program (headless sync/backup peer)
 xlog2 is an amateur-radio logger with GTK 4 and Qt frontends.
 .
 This package provides xlog2-syncd, a GUI-free backup peer: it joins the
 logbook sync mesh and keeps a full replica of the synced default logbook, and
 answers the mesh's distributed QRZ-cache queries while proactively enriching
 its own QRZ cache by looking up newly-synced callsigns on QRZ.com. It is meant
 to coexist with a GUI frontend on the same or a separate machine, keeping its
 own data directory and reading only the shared secret and QRZ credentials from
 the frontend's configuration.

Package: xlog2-data
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends}
Description: amateur-radio logging program (shared data)
 xlog2 is an amateur-radio logger with GTK 4 and Qt frontends.
 .
 This package provides architecture-independent runtime data shared by both
 frontends: the world-map coastline used by the map panel, and the udev rule
 that grants the local user access to the USB HID CW paddle.
